    {
      "source": "evaluator",
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, im working on a model and noticed my features have totally different scales. like one is 0-1 and another is 1000-5000. why do i actually need to normalize them before training? does it really matter that much?"
    },
    {
      "source": "target",
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Normalization is crucial because it prevents features with larger scales from dominating the learning process, much like how a loud person might be overlooked in a quiet room. If your model is optimized for the 0–1 scale, the 1000–5000 range will effectively be ignored, causing the model to converge slowly or fail to learn the correct relationships.\n\nImagine trying to teach a model to distinguish between a small grain of sand and a massive mountain; without standardizing their scales, the model will focus entirely on the mountain's size and miss the subtle details of the sand. In deep learning, this imbalance leads to unstable gradients, making the training process inefficient and prone to getting stuck in local minima.\n\nThink of it as a conversation where one person speaks in whispers and another shouts; the listener naturally focuses on the shout and misses the whisper. By normalizing both to a similar range, you ensure the model treats every feature with equal importance, allowing it to learn accurately and converge faster.",
